[{"id":43281,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In both, cases is about point of contact ring,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>R</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi></msqrt></math></p><p>Solid cylinder</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><msubsup><mi>v</mi><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>g</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>R</mi></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43409,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$-F(\\hat{i}-\\hat{j})$","$F(\\hat{i}-\\hat{j})$","$-F(\\hat{i}+\\hat{j})$","$F(\\hat{i}+\\hat{j})$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\vec{\\tau}=(-\\hat{i}+\\hat{j}) \\times(-F \\hat{k})$\n$=-F(\\hat{i}+\\hat{j})$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":43151,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["solid cylinder","ring","disc","solid sphere"],"answer":3,"solution":"By the law of conservation of mechanical energy, the total initial kinetic energy of the rolling object is converted into potential energy at the maximum height.<br><br>Total initial kinetic energy for an object rolling without slipping is given by:<br>$K = K_{\\text{translational}} + K_{\\text{rotational}}$<br>$K = \\dfrac{1}{2}mv_0^2 + \\dfrac{1}{2}I\\omega^2$<br><br>Substituting $\\omega = \\dfrac{v_0}{R}$ and $I = mk^2$ (where $k$ is the radius of gyration):<br>$K = \\dfrac{1}{2}mv_0^2 + \\dfrac{1}{2}(mk^2)\\left(\\dfrac{v_0}{R}\\right)^2 = \\dfrac{1}{2}mv_0^2\\left(1 + \\dfrac{k^2}{R^2}\\right)$<br><br>The potential energy at the maximum height $h$ is:<br>$U = mgh$<br><br>Given $h = \\dfrac{7v_0^2}{10g}$, we have:<br>$U = mg\\left(\\dfrac{7v_0^2}{10g}\\right) = \\dfrac{7}{10}mv_0^2$<br><br>Equating kinetic and potential energy ($K = U$):<br>$\\dfrac{1}{2}mv_0^2\\left(1 + \\dfrac{k^2}{R^2}\\right) = \\dfrac{7}{10}mv_0^2$<br><br>$1 + \\dfrac{k^2}{R^2} = \\dfrac{14}{10} = \\dfrac{7}{5}$<br><br>$\\dfrac{k^2}{R^2} = \\dfrac{7}{5} - 1 = \\dfrac{2}{5}$<br><br>The moment of inertia is $I = \\dfrac{2}{5}mR^2$, which corresponds to a solid sphere.<br><br>Answer: solid sphere","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43252,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02bb39c6-b080-47f6-9237-8a4237b14e03-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p>Moment of inertia of rod rotating about an axis passing through one end is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8943;</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Moment of inertia of ring rotating about one of its diameters is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Since the rod is bent into a ring, the circumference of the ring and the length of the rod are equal,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>R</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/322b3509-32b7-46b3-8e3c-fa1057ddab24-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 133px;\" /></p><p>Then,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn><msup><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Thus, the ratio&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><msup><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>, so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43205,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\frac{3}{2} \\omega$","$\\frac{5}{4} \\omega$","$\\frac{2}{3} \\omega$","$\\frac{4}{5} \\omega$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{I}_1 \\omega=\\mathrm{I}_2 \\omega_2 \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{MR}^2}{2} \\omega=\\frac{3}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{MR}^2}{2}\\right) \\omega_2 \\\\ & \\omega_2=\\frac{2}{3} \\omega\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43398,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\frac{5}{7}$ rotational and $\\frac{2}{7}$ translational","$\\frac{2}{7}$ rotational and $\\frac{5}{7}$ translational","$\\frac{2}{5}$ rotational and $\\frac{3}{5}$ translational","$\\frac{1}{2}$ rotational and $\\frac{1}{2}$ translational"],"answer":1,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& K . E_{\\text {rotational }}=\\frac{1}{2} I \\omega^2 \\\\\n& =\\frac{1}{2} \\frac{2}{5} \\omega r^2 d^2\\left(\\because I_{\\text {Solid sphere }}=\\frac{2}{5} m r^2\\right) \\\\\n& K \\cdot E_{\\text {translational }}=\\frac{1}{2} m v^2 \\\\\n& \\therefore \\frac{K \\cdot E_{\\text {rotational }}}{K \\cdot E_{\\text {translational }}}=\\frac{2}{5}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nHence option (b) is correct","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":43348,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{MR}^{2}$","$3 \\mathrm{MR}^{2}$","$\\frac{4}{5} \\mathrm{MR}^{2}$","$\\frac{2}{3} \\mathrm{MR}^{2}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Moment of inertia of disc $D_{1}$ about $O O^{\\prime}=I_{1}=\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}$\r\n\r\nM.O.I of $\\mathrm{D}_{2}$ about $\\mathrm{OO}^{\\prime}$ $=I_{2}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}\\right)+M R^{2}=\\frac{M R^{2}}{4}+M R^{2}$\r\n\r\nM.O.I of $\\mathrm{D}_{3}$ about $\\mathrm{OO}^{\\prime}$ $=I_{3}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}\\right)+M R^{2}=\\frac{M R^{2}}{4}+M R^{2}$\r\n\r\nso, resultant M.O.I about $\\mathrm{OO}^{\\prime}$ is $\\mathrm{I}=\\mathrm{I}_{1}+\\mathrm{I}_{2}+\\mathrm{I}_{3}$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\begin{aligned}\r\n\r\n\\Rightarrow & I=\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}+2\\left(\\frac{M R^{2}}{4}+M R^{2}\\right) \\\\\r\n\r\n&=\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}+\\frac{M R^{2}}{2}+2 M R^{2}=3 M R^{2}\r\n\r\n\\end{aligned}\r\n\r\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43206,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{6} \\mathrm{~m}$","$\\sqrt{5} \\mathrm{~m}$","$1 \\mathrm{~m}$","$2 \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{w}_{\\mathrm{g}}+\\mathrm{w}_{\\mathrm{Fr}}+\\mathrm{w}_{\\mathrm{s}}=\\Delta \\mathrm{KE} \\\\ & 5 \\times 10 \\times 5-0.5 \\times 5 \\times 10 \\times \\mathrm{x}-\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{Kx}^2=0-0 \\\\ & 250=25 \\mathrm{x}+50 \\mathrm{x}^2 \\\\ & 2 \\mathrm{x}^2+\\mathrm{x}-10=0 \\\\ & \\mathrm{x}=2\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43248,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Torque of pulley about its axis is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></math>, where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math>&nbsp;is moment of inertia and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>&nbsp;is angular acceleration.</p><p>Torque of a force about its axis is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>R</mi></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;is radius of pulley.</p><p>Then,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>12</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>&#945;</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Angular acceleration in terms of angular velocity is</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi>t</mi></msubsup><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p></blockquote><blockquote><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>or</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Now, using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, we have</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mn>6</mn></msubsup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>6</mn></msubsup></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>36</mn></math></p><p>Number&nbsp;of revolutions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>36</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>18</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43172,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For vertical rod with axis at end P: $I_1 = \\frac{ML^2}{3}$<br>For horizontal rod centered at distance L from P:<br>$I_2 = \\int_{-L/2}^{L/2} \\frac{M}{L}(x^2 + L^2)dx = \\frac{M}{L}\\left[\\frac{x^3}{3} + L^2x\\right]_{-L/2}^{L/2}$<br>$= \\frac{M}{L}\\left[\\frac{L^3}{12} + L^3\\right] = \\frac{13ML^2}{12}$<br>Total: $I = \\frac{ML^2}{3} + \\frac{13ML^2}{12} = \\frac{4ML^2 + 13ML^2}{12} = \\frac{17ML^2}{12}$<br>$x = 17$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43213,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1600</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1000</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Let the string makes angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> with the vertical. Weight will be balanced by the vertical component of tension, which is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></math> and the horizontal component towards the centre will provide the required centripetal force for circular motion. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>ω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><mo>=</mo></math>length of the string.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mn>400</mn><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo><msup><mi>ω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mi>rad</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43290,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>We know,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mi>t</mi></math></p><p>Let number of revolutions be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>900</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2460</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>26</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>728</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43375,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["go straight.","turn left and right alternately.","turn left.","turn right."],"answer":2,"solution":"<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image23-a206edbf-5200-49c4-b6b8-acab184d2f17.png\" /><br /><br />As roller moves forward radius of circle of left cone on track AB decreases. Thus right cone travel more distance compared to left and roller turns left","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":43312,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>g</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">g</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#8467;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">&#969;</mi><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#8467;</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Torque of centrifugal force&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mi>cf</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>dm</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mtext>&#952;&#969;</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>xcos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#977;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#952;cos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi><msubsup><mo>&#8747;</mo><mn>0</mn><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></msubsup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>dx</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mi>ef</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos&#952;</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mi>mg</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mi>cf</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mg</mi><mo>.</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin&#952;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43186,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\alpha$","$\\alpha / 4$","$\\alpha / 8$","$\\alpha / 2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mVsxC_8RydLIrdnKP5T0lz20itJ0pD2GK3y_aO6z1IE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\alpha=\\frac{\\mathrm{M} \\ell^2}{12}$<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZLig7_We2VTKkJqbt1HKJHVgYbw3HAIqDj3rG7eXMsE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\alpha^{\\prime}=2\\left[\\frac{\\frac{\\mathrm{M}}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\ell}{2}\\right)^2}{12}\\right] \\\\ & \\alpha^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\mathrm{M} \\ell^2}{48}=\\frac{\\alpha}{4}\\end{aligned}$<br/>Correct option is (2)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43167,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["0.72","0.36","0.18","0.63"],"answer":3,"solution":"For two solid spheres in contact with the tangent line at the contact point.<br>Sphere 1: $m_1 = 5$ kg, $r_1 = 0.1$ m<br>Sphere 2: $m_2 = 10$ kg, $r_2 = 0.2$ m<br>For a solid sphere, $I_{cm} = \\frac{2}{5}mr^2$<br>The tangent at contact is perpendicular to the line joining centers. The perpendicular distance from each sphere's center to this tangent line equals its radius.<br>Using parallel axis theorem: $I_{total} = I_{cm} + md^2$<br>For sphere 1: $I_1 = \\frac{2}{5}(5)(0.1)^2 + 5(0.1)^2 = 0.02 + 0.05 = 0.07$ kg·m²<br>For sphere 2: $I_2 = \\frac{2}{5}(10)(0.2)^2 + 10(0.2)^2 = 0.16 + 0.4 = 0.56$ kg·m²<br>Total: $I = 0.07 + 0.56 = 0.63$ kg·m²","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43418,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}}=0$ and $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}} . \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}} \\neq 0$","$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}} \\neq 0$ and $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}}=0$","$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}} \\neq 0$ and $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}} \\neq 0$","$\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}}=0$ and $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{F}} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{T}}=0$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":43288,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>,</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>,</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>,</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>,</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mover><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mover><mi>j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mover><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mover><mi>j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mover><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mover><mi>j</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p><p>Torque about <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi>O</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>&#964;</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mi>O</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mover><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mover><mi>k</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p><p>Torque about <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>&#964;</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mi>Q</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mover><mi>F</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mover><mi>k</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43372,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">cos</mi></mrow><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">sin</mi></mrow><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">sin</mi></mrow><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">cos</mi></mrow><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Moment of a force about&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>O</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mfrac><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>s</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#8289;</mo><mi>&#952;</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":43178,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"When sphere is of radius $R$, its mass is $M$, when radius is reduced to $\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{2}$, mass will reduced to $\\frac{\\mathrm{M}}{8}$ Now by conservation of angular momentum<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\left(\\tau_{e x t}=0\\right) \\\\\n& L_1=L_2 \\\\\n& I_1 \\omega_1=I_2 \\omega_2 \\\\\n& \\left(\\frac{2}{5} M R^2\\right) \\omega_1=\\left(\\frac{2}{5}\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{M}}{8}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{2}\\right)^2\\right) \\omega_2<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\omega_2=32 \\omega_1$ value of x is 32<br/>Answer is 32","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43370,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["Every object that is weighed using this balance appears lighter than its actual weight","Left arm is shorter than the right arm","Both the arms are of same length","Left arm is longer than the right arm"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Let <math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>m</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <msub> <mi>m</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math> be the masses of pan<br /><br />It is given that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WhatsApp_Image_2020-05-19_at_3.12.18_AM.jpeg\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 174px;\" /><br /><br />Since&nbsp;balance is achieved, so net torque about <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>O</mi></math> should be zero.<br /><math> <mrow> <mfenced> <mrow> <mn>5</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>+</mo><msub> <mi>m</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mi>g</mi></mrow> </mfenced><msub> <mi>r</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mfenced> <mrow> <msub> <mi>m</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mi>g</mi></mrow> </mfenced><msub> <mi>r</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfenced><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfenced><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>g</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>So, left arm is shorter than the right arm.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43182,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Applying Mechanical Energy conservation :<br/>$\\mathrm{k}_{\\mathrm{i}}+\\mathrm{U}_{\\mathrm{i}}=\\mathrm{k}_{\\mathrm{f}}+\\mathrm{U}_{\\mathrm{f}}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\Rightarrow 0+\\mathrm{Mgh}=\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{mv}^2\\left(1+\\frac{\\mathrm{k}^2}{\\mathrm{R}^2}\\right)+0 \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{~V}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2 \\mathrm{gh}}{1+\\frac{\\mathrm{k}^2}{\\mathrm{R}^2}}}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>So Ratio of velocities<br/>$\\frac{\\mathrm{V}_{\\text {Ring }}}{\\mathrm{V}_{\\text {solids sphere }}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{1+\\frac{2}{5}}{1+1}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{7}{10}}$<br/>$\\mathrm{x}=3.5$ Rounding off $\\mathrm{x}=4$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43317,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/31c19e53-5ae5-4d3b-9bea-06ff702974f0-image.png\" style=\"width: 125px; height: 160px;\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7fc25a95-4ba0-4c92-9e64-6aebb9a7d711-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 158px;\" />&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7df04302-ea6e-40ac-b5e9-4e06861e9fc7-image.png\" style=\"width: 117px; height: 153px;\" /></p><p>Common angular velocity from angular momentum conversation</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>l</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math><br />Final K.E.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43242,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f7735e0a-6334-4508-a46e-b593bb9c1ec9-9894275.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 289px;\" /></p><p>We have,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>CM</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p>Since <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi></math> is parallel to diameter and at a distance of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;from it, using parallel axis theorem,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>AB</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Thus, the ratio is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>AB</mi></msub><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>CM</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43227,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The kinetic energy is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>I</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p>It is given that the new moment of inertia</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>I</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>I</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Clearly, the final kinetic energy is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>I</mi><mo>'</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi>I</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mi>E</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43219,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5bf2fcab-05e6-477e-8ae4-2d030369d4e1.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 179px;\"/></p><p>For rolling motion, the acceleration of the cylinder along the inclined plane can be expressed as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>The moment of inertia of the cylinder can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>M</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equations (1) and (2), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>a</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>×</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>10</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math></p><p>Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43201,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"At $t=1$\n$r_{A B}=-1 \\hat{i}+(3 n+1) \\hat{j}+(2-4 p) \\hat{k}$\n\nAt $t=1$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& v_A=2 \\hat{i}+3 n \\hat{j}+2 \\hat{k} \\\\\n& v_B=2 \\hat{i}-2 \\hat{j}+4 p \\hat{k} \\\\\n& \\vec{v}_A-\\vec{v}_B=0, \\quad 4-6 n+8 p=0\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{gathered}\\left|v_A\\right|=\\left|v_B\\right| \\quad(3 n)^2+4=4+16 p^2 \\\\ 3 n=-4 p \\\\ 4+16 p=0 \\\\ p=-\\frac{1}{4}, n=\\frac{1}{3} \\\\ r_{A B}=-\\hat{i}+2 \\hat{j}+3 \\hat{k} \\\\ v_A=2 \\hat{i}+\\hat{j}+2 \\hat{k} \\\\ \\therefore L=m\\left|\\vec{r}_{A B} \\times \\vec{v}_A\\right|=90\\end{gathered}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43171,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$m g / 4$","$m g / 2$","$m g / 3$","mg"],"answer":0,"solution":"When string at B is cut, rod rotates about A.<br>Torque about A: $\\tau = mg \\times \\frac{l}{2}$<br>Moment of inertia about A: $I_A = \\frac{ml^2}{3}$<br>Angular acceleration: $\\alpha = \\frac{mg \\cdot l/2}{ml^2/3} = \\frac{3g}{2l}$<br>Acceleration of COM: $a_{cm} = \\alpha \\times \\frac{l}{2} = \\frac{3g}{4}$<br>Newton's second law: $mg - T = ma_{cm}$<br>$T = mg - \\frac{3mg}{4} = \\frac{mg}{4}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43200,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$\\frac{7}{32} \\mathrm{MR}^2$","$\\frac{9}{32} \\mathrm{MR}^2$","$\\frac{17}{32} \\mathrm{MR}^2$","$\\frac{13}{32} \\mathrm{MR}^2$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/M01VSsfAguNI4rXoEPwBjy_ShsUfVP5k2MO4laHx5ck.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$\\begin{aligned} & I_{\\text {complete }}=\\frac{M R^2}{2} \\\\ & \\begin{aligned} I_{\\text {removed }} & =\\left(\\frac{M}{4}\\right)\\left(\\frac{R}{2}\\right)^2 \\frac{1}{2}+\\left(\\frac{M}{4}\\right)\\left(\\frac{R}{2}\\right)^2 \\\\ & =\\frac{3 M R^2}{32} \\\\ I=\\frac{M R^2}{2} & -\\frac{3 M R^2}{32}=\\frac{13}{32} M R^2\\end{aligned}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43422,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["mvL","mvl","mvr","zero"],"answer":3,"solution":"Zero, line of motion through the point P.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":43325,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Using work-energy theorem&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mgh</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>mv</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>Iω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mgh</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>mω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><msup><mi>mr</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; ( since&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>mr</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>rω</mi></math>&nbsp;)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>mgh</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>mω</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Hence,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ω</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>gh</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msqrt></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43263,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let the mass of the scale be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>.</p><p>The centre of mass of the scale will be at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p><p>Applying torque balance,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>50</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>40</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>g</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43403,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["$-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\cos \\theta \\hat{i}+\\frac{v^2}{R} \\sin \\theta \\hat{j}$","$-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\sin \\theta \\hat{i}+\\frac{v^2}{R} \\cos \\theta \\hat{j}$","$-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\cos \\theta \\hat{i}-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\sin \\theta \\hat{j}$","$\\frac{v^2}{R} \\hat{i}+\\frac{v^2}{R} \\hat{j}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"For a particle in uniform circular motion,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{a}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}^2}{\\mathrm{R}} \\text { towards centre of circle } \\\\\n& \\therefore \\quad \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{a}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}^2}{\\mathrm{R}}(-\\cos \\theta \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}-\\sin \\theta \\hat{\\mathrm{j}}) \\\\\n& \\text { or } \\quad \\vec{a}=-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\cos \\theta \\hat{i}-\\frac{v^2}{R} \\sin \\theta \\hat{j} \\\\\n&\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kP0H7gFebMfdqUaFix_vbN8v0l76pkJk50cDFNvcdPI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":43266,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["remains same in magnitude but changes in the direction","remains same in magnitude and direction","is zero","changes in magnitude but remains same in the direction"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21aa058b-df68-46ba-94ed-4f0cccddb901-f6aa0c30-3119-4458-b817-758d96f3f930-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 217px;\" /><br />The angular momentum is defined as the vector product of linear momentum and perpendicular distance,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>L</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mover><mi>p</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mover><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>m</mi><mover><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>,&nbsp;And direction will be upward &amp; remain constant.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43237,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Rotational Motion","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Acceleration of the disc,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>k</mi></msub><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p><p>Now, velocity of the centre of mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Now total kinetic energy during pure rolling(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>r</mi></math>) will become,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfrac><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]